{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>ATP:cob(I)alamin (or ATP:corrinoid) adenosyltransferases ([ec:2.5.1.17]), catalyse the conversion of cobalamin (vitamin B12) into its coenzyme form, adenosylcobalamin (AdoCbl)or coenzyme B12 [[cite:PUB00035324]]. AdoCbl contains an adenosyl moiety liganded to the cobalt ion of cobalamin via a covalent Co-C bond. AdoCbl is required as a cofactor for the activity of certain enzymes.</p>\n\n<p>ATP:cob(I)alamin adenosyltransferases are classed into three groups: CobA-type [[cite:PUB00035323]], EutT-type [[cite:PUB00015064]] and PduO-type [[cite:PUB00013593]]. Each of the three enzyme types appears to be specialised for particular AdoCbl-dependent enzymes or for the de novo synthesis AdoCbl. PduO and EutT are distantly related, sharing short conserved motifs, while CobA is evolutionarily unrelated and is an example of convergent evolution.</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false} {"text" "<p>This entry represents Corrinoid adenosyltransferase EutT and similar proteins predominantly found in Gammaproteobacteria. They convert cyanocobalamin (CN-B12) to adenosylcobalamin (AdoCbl), the inducer of the eut operon [[cite:PUB00035325], [cite:PUB00097910]]. Bacteria that harbour the ethanolamine utilization pathway can use ethanolamine a source of carbon and nitrogen [[cite:PUB00014698]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR036451", "name" "Cobalamin adenosyltransferase-like superfamily", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"pirsf" {"PIRSF012294" "ATP:cob(I)alamin adenosyltransferase, EutT type"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Corrinoid adenosyltransferase EutT", "short" "AdoTrfase_EutT"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 0, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 180, "taxa" 1267, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 1307, "sets" 0, "protein